ase-modifying antirheumatic drugs." Drugs Aging 13 (1998): 281-9[4] Osman MA, Patel RB, Schuna A, Sundstrom WR, Welling PG "Reduction in oral penicillamine absorption by food, antacid and ferrous sulfate." Clin Pharmacol Ther 33 (1983): 465-70[5] "Product Information. Cuprimine (penicillamine)." Merck & Co, Inc, West Point, PA.[6] Cerner Multum, Inc. "Australian Product Information." O 0', 1767369485);
